#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it feels like to fly a small airplane, I would say it's like riding a motorcycle or all-terrain vehicle combined with a boat, all while flying at 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, conditions change rapidly. There is a certain degree of instability on the ground, so motorcycles or all-terrain vehicles are needed.
Additionally, you might not know that when flying a plane on the ground, you control the direction with your feet, not with the control stick. You use the rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel turbulence and shaking, which feels just like sailing on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents may make you feel dizzy and disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just as sailors adapt to sailing on the sea.
As for this, there's also a random little tidbit:
Flying is very tiring. Today my back and legs are aching badly, feeling as if I had gone to the gym and worked out.
This isn't as simple as driving out for a Sunday drive. In my eyes, as a beginner, it's more like a sport than just a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday! Welcome to 4,000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
The weather was a bit unstable today, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped as low as 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
The weather is clear today, and although there is a bit of haze in the sky, the view is still great.
